# In-Code Documentation

Production code in `src/main/java` must carry meaningful documentation. Comments explain **why** and **what callers may rely on** — not what the code literally does.

Canonical project docs (`DOMAIN_LANGUAGE.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`) cover vocabulary and system-wide structure. In-code docs cover **type and method contracts** at the point of use.

## Requirements

1. **Document production code** — Every public type and public/protected member needs Javadoc. Package-private and private members need a comment when behavior, invariants, or trade-offs are not obvious from the signature alone.
2. **No obvious comments** — Do not restate the name, parameter list, or control flow. If the comment adds no information beyond reading the code, delete it.
3. **Contract-first Javadoc** — Describe how to use the API, preconditions, postconditions, return semantics, thrown exceptions, and thread-safety. Call out JSONata-spec alignment when relevant.
4. **Local architecture decisions** — Class-level Javadoc (or a focused block comment on non-trivial private logic) must explain *why* this type exists, which layer it belongs to, and non-obvious design choices (e.g. why a port/adapter split, why immutability, why delegation).

## What to include

| Element | Document |
|---------|----------|
| Public class / interface / record | Purpose, layer role, main usage pattern, invariants |
| Public method | Parameters, return value (including empty/absent cases), `@throws`, side effects |
| Factory / builder | Valid inputs, defaults, what is *not* validated here |
| Domain type | JSONata meaning, mapping to spec terms, immutability |
| Non-obvious branch | *Why* the branch exists (spec rule, performance, layer boundary) |

Use standard `@param`, `@return`, `@throws` consistently. Link related types with `{@link …}`.

## Examples

```java
// ❌ Obvious — restates the code
/** Returns the arity. */
public int arity() { return function.parameterNames().size(); }

// ✅ Contract — tells callers what the value means
/**
 * Number of positional parameters this function accepts before partial application.
 * Does not include the implicit context argument injected by {@link FunctionApplyService}.
 */
public int arity() { ... }
```

```java
// ❌ Implementation narration
// Loop through args and apply signature coercion

// ✅ Architecture + contract
/**
 * Adapts call-site arguments to the declared {@link FunctionSignature}.
 * Lives in the domain layer so built-ins and user functions share one coercion path;
 * Jackson details stay in infrastructure adapters.
 */
```

```java
// ❌ Duplicates ARCHITECTURE.md
/**
 * JSONata.java is the facade. It parses expressions and evaluates them.
 * See the architecture doc for the full pipeline.
 */

// ✅ Local decision at the type
/**
 * Application entry point for compile-once, evaluate-many usage.
 * Holds a compiled {@link Mapping} and delegates evaluation to domain types;
 * parsing stays in {@code parser} and is not repeated per {@link #evaluate(Data)} call.
 */
public final class JSONata { ... }
```

## Scope boundaries

- **Tests** (`src/test/java`) — follow `tdd-workflow.mdc`; Gherkin-style comments on scenarios, not full Javadoc on every helper.
- **Generated code** (`target/`, ANTLR output) — do not edit; document in `.g4` or listener classes instead.
- **Project-wide vocabulary and diagrams** — `DOMAIN_LANGUAGE.md` and `ARCHITECTURE.md`, updated per `documentation-workflow.mdc`.

## Anti-patterns

- Commenting every line or every private getter
- Javadoc that only copies the method name into a sentence
- Spec behavior documented only in tests with no type-level contract
- Long essays in comments that belong in canonical docs — summarize locally, link outward when useful

## Checklist (before finishing a Java change)

- [ ] New/changed public API has Javadoc with usage and expectations
- [ ] Non-obvious logic has a *why* comment, not a *what* comment
- [ ] Architecture role of new types is clear from class-level Javadoc
- [ ] No obvious or stale comments left behind
